To solve this trigonometric equation, we can start by simplifying the expression.
\begin{align*} \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \cos 40^\circ + \sin x^\circ \\ 2\sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= 2\cos 40^\circ + 2\sin x^\circ \\ 2\sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \sin 30^\circ + \sin 50^\circ + 2\sin x^\circ.
\end{align*} 

Next, we apply the sum-to-product identities to the right side of the equation.
\begin{align*} 2\sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= 2\sin 40^\circ \cos 10^\circ + 2\sin x^\circ \\ \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \sin 40^\circ \cos 10^\circ + \sin x^\circ \\ \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \frac{1}{2}(\sin 50^\circ + \sin 30^\circ) + \sin x^\circ.
\end{align*}
At this point, we have an opportunity to use the sum-to-product identities to simplify the expression further.
\begin{align*} \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \frac{1}{2}(2\sin 40^\circ \cos 10^\circ) + \sin x^\circ \\ \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \sin 40^\circ \cos 10^\circ + \sin x^\circ.
\end{align*}
Now, we can use the product-to-sum identities to simplify the expression yet again.
\begin{align*} \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \sin 40^\circ \cos 10^\circ + \sin x^\circ \\ \sqrt{3} \cos 10^\circ &= \sin 50^\circ + \sin x^\circ.
\end{align*}

Finally, we solve for x.
\begin{align*} x &= 40^\circ \end{align*}

Therefore, the solution is $x = 40^\circ$.
